public class Main {
    static class BankAccount {
        private double balance;
        BankAccount(double b) { balance = b; }

        // synchronized ensures atomicity:
        synchronized void transfer(BankAccount to, double amount) {
            if (balance >= amount) {
                balance -= amount;
                to.balance += amount;
            }
        }

        synchronized double getBalance() { return balance; }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) throws InterruptedException {
        BankAccount a = new BankAccount(1000);
        BankAccount b = new BankAccount(1000);

        Thread[] threads = new Thread[10];
        for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
            threads[i] = new Thread(() -> a.transfer(b, 10));
            threads[i].start();
        }
        for (Thread t : threads) t.join();

        System.out.println("A: " + a.getBalance());
        System.out.println("B: " + b.getBalance());
        System.out.println("Total: " + (a.getBalance() + b.getBalance()));
    }
}

instruction:
Creating threads is expensive. A **thread pool** reuses threads:

```java
ExecutorService pool = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(4);
pool.submit(() -> { /* task */ });
pool.shutdown();
```

Always `shutdown()` when done — otherwise the program won't exit.

